          %td= t("рѣѕ-ат", "rědzát", :linebreak => true)
          %td= t("луб-ат", "lúbat", :linebreak => true)
          %td= t("пихь-ут", "píhjut", :linebreak => true)
      %p Note that the #{abbrev '3sg'} ending in the first conjugation is pronounced /s/, not /st/ as the spelling would suggest. The final -т/-ти is also never pronounced in the #{abbrev '3pl'} forms: цидати [tsi.ˈda] “they read”, пихьут [ˈpi.çʊ] “they write”.</p>
      %p All of the above thematic forms are created using the pattern <span class="pattern">stem + thematic vowel + ending</span>, except in the #{abbrev '1sg'} and #{abbrev '3pl'}, where the thematic vowel is dropped.
      %p In the verbs лубити and пизати, the root-final consonants /z/ and /l/ undergo palatalizations to /ç/ and /bl/ in some forms. Such mutations are common in the second and third conjugations. Common present-tense mutations include:
      %ul
        %li с, з, ш, ж → хь (#{t "пизати", "pizáti"} “write” → #{t "пихьун", "píhjun"})
        %li з, ж → ғь (#{t "везати", "vezáti"} “tie, connect” → #{t "веғьун", "véğjun"})
        %li т → кь (#{t "вратити", "vrátiti"} “return” → #{t "вракьун", "vrákjun"})
        %li д → гь (#{t "видѣти", "víděti"} “see” → #{t "вигьун", "vígjun"})
        %li н → нь (#{t "хранити", "hraníti"} “keep” → #{t "храньун", "hranjún"})
        %li ст, ск → шкь (#{t "ескати", "ieskáti"} “search for” → #{t "ешкьун", "iéśkjun"})
        %li зд, зг → жгь (#{t "ѣздити", "iě́zditi"} “go by vehicle” → #{t "ѣжгьун", "iě́źgjun"})
        %li г → ж (#{t "бѣйкьи", "bě́ikji"} “run” → #{t "бѣжун", "bě́źun"})
        %li к → ц (#{t "плайкьи", "pláikji"} → #{t "плацун", "plácun"})
      %p In some verbs, such as вратити, видѣти, хранити, ескати, and ѣздити above, these alterations occur only in the first person singular. In addition to the above, the following changes may occur in the #{abbrev '1sg'} only:
      %ul
        %li п, б, в, м → пл, бл, ўл, мл (#{t "лубити", "lubíti"} → #{t "лублун", "lublún"})
      %p There is no clear way to know for certain whether a verb root will have a palatalization in all forms, only in the #{abbrev '1sg'}, or in no forms, without looking at the history. Palatalizations in all forms arise from an historical /j/ element in the root, no longer visible. In the #{abbrev '1sg'}, it derives from a palatalization caused by the ending. No palatalization occurs when a root entered the language after the distintegration of Common Slavic, unless it later gained one by analogy, or if the verb was borrowed with all of its irregularities from Russian or acquired gradation from a Uralic language. There is, however, a tendency in Novegradian to generalize all but the labial palatalizations to all forms (e.g., бѣйкьи “run”, which now has <i>g</i> → <i>ź</i> in all forms though it originated in only the #{abbrev '1sg'}/#{abbrev '3pl'}). Colloquial speech shows considerably more generalization than the standard.

    = section "Irregularities in the Present-Future Tense" do
      %p Within the second and third conjugations, there are many minor verb classes involving a suffix that appears and disappears or with vanishing epenthetic vowels. These create the most problematic irregularities to learn, as the rules can be complex and the set of verbs they apply to often are rather small. However, since each describes a number of verbs, they cannot be considered one-of-a-kind irregularities, but must rather be regarded as minor subclasses of third conjugation verbs.
      %ul
        %li First conjugation verbs with <i>-ova-</i> suffix:
      %p The <i>-ova-</i> suffix is a common means by which imperfective verbs are derived from perfective verbs (see Derivational Morphology and Word Creation section 10.3.3). In general usage in the modern language, verbs with such a suffix behave as regular first conjugation verbs. However, in more archaic or poetic language, these verbs actually behave as part of the third conjugation and conjugate irregularly. In the present tense, the suffix <i>-ova-</i> becomes <i>-ui-</i>. It is important to note, however, that this is no longer the case in the modern standard language.
      %p The <i>-ui-</i> suffix is always stressed.
      - cyr = %w[кѣл-у-юн кѣл-у-еш кѣл-у-ет кѣл-у-ева кѣл-у-ета кѣл-у-ета кѣл-у-ем кѣл-у-ете кѣл-у-ют]
      - lat = %w[kělúiun kělúieś kělúiet kělúieva kělúieta kělúieta kělúiem kělúiete kělúiut]
      = render 'present_future_verb_table', :infinitive => {:cyr => "кѣловати", :lat => "kělováti"}, :meaning => "kiss", :aspect => "impf", :cyrillic => cyr, :latin => lat
      %p There are a few verbs, such as #{t "ковати", "kóvati"} “forge”, that retain <i>-ui-</i> in the present tense, but nowadays take first conjugation endings.
      - cyr = %w[к-у-ям к-у-яш к-у-яст к-у-ява к-у-яcта к-у-яcта к-у-яме к-у-яте к-у-яти]
      - lat = %w[kúiam kúiaś kúiast kúiava kúiasta kúiasta kúiame kúiate kúiati]
      = render 'present_future_verb_table', :infinitive => {:cyr => "ковати", :lat => "kóvati"}, :meaning => "forge", :aspect => "impf", :cyrillic => cyr, :latin => lat
      %ul
        %li Third conjugation verbs with <i>-а-</i> in the infinitive:
      %p Third conjugation verbs with <i>-a-</i> in the infinitive always undergo a consonant mutation in all forms (if possible), and never have mobile stress in the present/future tense. #{t "Пизати", "pizáti"} “write” above is one example, a stem-stressed verb. #{t "Медати", "medáti"} “cast, throw, hurl” is another, an ending-stressed verb.
      - cyr = %w[мегь-ун мегь-еш мегь-ет мегь-ева мегь-ета мегь-ета мегь-ем мегь-ете мегь-ут]
      - lat = %w[megjún megjéś megjét megjéva megjéta megjéta megjém megjéte megjút]
      = render 'present_future_verb_table', :infinitive => {:cyr => "медати", :lat => "medáti"}, :meaning => "cast, throw, hurl", :aspect => "impf", :cyrillic => cyr, :latin => lat
      %ul
        %li Second and Third conjugation verbs with <i>-e-</i> in the infinitive:
      %p Second and Third conjugation verbs with <i>-e-</i> (or, very rarely, <i>-ě-</i>) as the infinitive vowel are the result of an early metathesis in Old Novegradian. For example, #{t "прети", "préti"} “support” comes from Common Slavic *perti, whose present/future stem was *pьr-. The result is an ending-stressed verb that appears to gain a vowel in the present tense not present in the infinitive. Note that прети was originally third conjugation, but is now second.
      - cyr = %w[пер-ун пер-иш пер-ит пер-ива пер-ита пер-ита пер-им пер-ите пер-ат]
      - lat = %w[perún períś perít períva períta períta perím períte perát]
      = render 'present_future_verb_table', :infinitive => {:cyr => "прети", :lat => "préti"}, :meaning => "support, hold up", :aspect => "impf", :cyrillic => cyr, :latin => lat
      %p #{t "Мерети", "meréti"} “die, stop working” (#{abbrev 'pf'}), which is third conjugation, is also a member of this class. However, the expected infinitive *мрети is never found because an epenthetic /e/ was inserted to prevent the /mr/- cluster. The verb therefore appears to be completely regular, although it is always ending-stressed.
      %p A few other verbs appear to have /e ~ æ/ as their infinitive vowel, but in fact do not. #{t "Старѣти", "starě́ti"} “age”, for example, is underlyingly *старѣйти. #{t "Радеети", "radéieti"} “enjoy” has the similar root *радей-, but does not appear as *радети because it is a more recent loan from Komi радейтны. Because the /j/ was present in the original Komi verb, an attempt is made to preserve it in the Novegradian infinitive as well by inserting an epenthetic /e/.
      %ul
        %li Third conjugation verbs with vanishing <i>-a-</i> in the infinitive:
      %p This class of verbs is similar to the above in that there is an additional vowel found in the present/future stem not seen in the infinitive. This class, however, includes more verbs than the above, and the extra vowel in the present tense is not as predictable, since it can be either /e/ (from CS *ь) or /o/ (from CS *ъ). There are never any mutations seen in these verbs.
      - cyr = %w[бер-ун бер-еш бер-ет бер-ева бер-ета бер-ета бер-ем бер-ете бер-ут]
      - lat = %w[berún beréś berét beréva beréta beréta berém beréte berút]
