      %p Notice how the full verb root is only visible in the #{abbrev '3pl'} form of each verb. Before /t/ root-final *d weakens to /s/, and before /m s β/ it drops entirely. The root-final *s of буити has fewer problems with other consonants, and in fact in the #{abbrev '1dl'} form it remains intact before the suffixed <i>-va</i> (which weakens to <i>-ua</i>).
      %p Unlike most other Slavic languages, the #{abbrev '3pl'} form of буити is no longer completely irregular. As late as the 18th century it was still pronounced #{t "сат", "sát"}, but the prefixed <i>ie-</i> was added to bring it more in line with the other forms.
      %p The spellings for a number of the athematic forms are outdated, reflecting older pronunciations. #{t "Есм", "iésm"} “I am” is usually pronounced [ˈjɛ.smɪ] (formally) or [ˈjɛm] (commonly). The forms ending in -ст are pronounced with just the /s/ (so #{t "ест", "iést"} “it is” is [ˈjɛs], etc). The athematic #{abbrev '3pl'} ending -ит is pronounced [ə], the result of есат’s ending being generalized to replace an ending that seemed too similar to third person singular of many thematic verbs: вѣдит “they know” [ˈβæ.də].
