  = section "The Analytic Future Tenses" do
    %p The two analytic future tenses both require the use of the future tense of буити “be” as an auxiliary verb. Буити is the only verb in Novegradian with a true, distinct future tense. It is formed by adding the regular third conjugation present/future endings onto the stem #{t "*бад-", "*bad-"}.
    %p The simple future, which only imperfective verbs can have, is formed using the future form of “be” followed by the infinitive. With цидати “read”:
    - cyr = ["бадун цидати", "бадеш цидати", "бадет цидати", "бадева цидати", "бадета цидати", "бадета цидати", "бадем цидати", "бадете цидати", "бадут цидати"]
    - lat = ["bádun cidáti", "bádeś cidáti", "bádet cidáti", "bádeva cidáti", "bádeta cidáti", "bádeta cidáti", "bádem cidáti", "bádete cidáti", "bádut cidáti"]
    = render 'present_future_verb_table', :infinitive => {:cyr => "цидати", :lat => "cidáti"}, :meaning => "read", :aspect => "impf", :cyrillic => cyr, :latin => lat
    %p However, the simple future of “be” is always бадун, бадеш, etc, never **бадун буити.
    %p The future tense form of “be” combined with a past tense verb, the L-form of either a perfective or imperfective verb, forms the future hypothetical tense. With рѣѕити “say, read aloud”:
    - cyr = ["бадун рѣѕиле", "бадеш рѣѕиле", "бадет рѣѕиле", "бадева рѣѕилѣ", "бадета рѣѕилѣ", "бадета рѣѕилѣ", "бадем рѣѕили", "бадете рѣѕили", "бадут рѣѕили"]
    - lat = ["bádun rědzíle", "bádeś rědzíle", "bádet rědzíle", "bádeva rědzílě", "bádeta rědzílě", "bádeta rědzílě", "bádem rědzíli", "bádete rědzíli", "bádut rědzíli"]
    = render 'present_future_verb_table', :infinitive => {:cyr => "рѣѕити", :lat => "rědzíti"}, :meaning => "say, read aloud", :aspect => "impf", :cyrillic => cyr, :latin => lat
    %p The singular forms will all conjugate to agree in gender, as in the past tense. Unlike in the simple future, the form бадун буиле is allowed.

  = section "Verbs of Motion" do
    %p Verbs of motion form a special class in Novegradian, like in other Slavic languages, as instead of a two-way distinction of perfective-imperfective, there is a three-way distinction where the imperfective is divided into determinate and indeterminate forms. Unlike the other Slavic languages, however, the perfective of verbs of motion is falling out of use. In modern Novegradian, it is almost never used in the past tense and only finds use to indicate the future. The perfective is always formed by adding the prefix #{t "по-", "po-"} to the determinate form. The indeterminate is formed from a separate root, though usually related somehow to the determinate root.
    %p Such triplets include (#{abbrev 'det.impf'} ~ #{abbrev 'pf'} ~ #{abbrev 'indet.impf'}):
    %ul
      %li #{t "исти", "ísti"} ~ #{t "пойсти", "póisti"} ~ #{t "ходити", "hóditi"} “go, walk”
      %li #{t "ѣcати", "iě́sati"} ~ #{t "поѣcати", "poiě́sati"} ~ #{t "ѣздити", "iě́zditi"} “go, travel, go by vehicle”
      %li #{t "бѣйкьи", "bě́ikji"} ~ #{t "побѣйкьи", "pobě́ikji"} ~ #{t "бѣгати", "bě́gati"} “run”
      %li #{t "ледѣти", "ledě́ti"} ~ #{t "поледѣти", "poledě́ti"} ~ #{t "лидати", "lidáti"} “fly”
      %li #{t "плути", "plúti"} ~ #{t "поплути", "poplúti"} ~ #{t "плавити", "pláviti"} “swim, sail, float”
      %li #{t "нести", "nésti"} ~ #{t "понести", "ponésti"} ~ #{t "ношити", "nóśiti"} “carry”
      %li #{t "везти", "vézti"} ~ #{t "повезти", "povézti"} ~ #{t "вожити", "vóźiti"} “transport”
