= section "The Imperative Mood" do
  %p There are five imperative forms (#{abbrev '2sg'}, #{abbrev '2dl'}, #{abbrev '2pl'}, #{abbrev '1dl'}, #{abbrev '1pl'}) for both perfective and imperfective roots. Generally speaking, the #{abbrev '2sg'} is formed from the present/future stem by adding #{t "-ай", "-ái"} (first conjugation) or #{t "-и", "-í"} (second and third conjugations). The #{abbrev '2dl'} is formed by adding #{t "-айта", "-áita"} (first), #{t "-ита", "-íta"} (second), or #{t "-ѣта", "-ě́ta"} (third). The #{abbrev '2pl'} is the same, but with the plural #{t "-те", "-te"} instead of the dual -та.
  %p The first person imperatives add these same endings to the #{abbrev '1dl'} or #{abbrev '1pl'} present/future forms, dropping any final vowel if there is one (except for the third conjugation, which has -ѣута/-ѣмте instead of -еута/-емте). If the root undergoes a palatalization in all forms of the present/future tnese, that palatalization will also appear in the imperatives. These suffixes are always stressed.
  %p Only third conjugation verbs show the vowel alteration /i~æ/ in their imperative forms. This predates Proto-Slavic, but has largely been levelled out in most Slavic languages other than Bulgarian and Czech.
  %p Although the stress in the imperative form is always on the ending, even in otherwise stem-stressed verbs, this never results in the appearance of a voiced consonant that does not appear anywhere else in a particular verb’s paradigm. Thus the #{abbrev '2sg'} imperative “write!” is #{t "пихьи", "pihjí"}, not expected #{t "**пиғьи", "piğjí"} by the pretonic voicing sound law, because /ʝ/ does not appear in any other form of пизати.
