= section "Participles" do
  %p Modern Novegradian has three verbal participles: active imperfective, passive perfective, and passive imperfective. With a verb such as “write”, these are roughly equivalent to English “writing”, “written”, and “being written”, respectively. However, it is important to note that these participles are organized by aspect, not by tense.
  %p The active imperfective participle is formed from the present/future stem. First and third conjugation verbs then add #{t "-акь-", "-akj-"}, while second conjugation verbs add #{t "-екь-", "-ekj-"}. If there is a palatalization in all forms of the present tense that originates in Common Slavic, it is also seen in the participle: #{t "пизати", "pizáti"} “write” → #{abbrev 'pres'} #{t "*пихь-", "*pihj-"} → #{t "пихьакье", "pihjákje"} “writing”. However, if there is a palatalization that did not arise predictably from Common Slavic but by later analogy, it is not seen in the participle: #{t "мойкьи", "móikji"} “be able” → #{abbrev 'pres'} #{t "*муз-", "*muz-"} → #{t "могакье", "mogákje"} “able”. Palatalizations only in the #{abbrev '1sg'} form are not extended to the participle: #{t "лубити", "lubíti"} “love” → #{abbrev 'pres'} #{t "*луб(л)-", "*lub(l)-"} → #{t "лубекье", "lubékje"} “loving”.
  %p The passive imperfective participle is formed from the present/future stem just as the active imperfective, with the same rules regarding palatalizations. First conjugation verbs then add #{t "-ам-", "-am-"}, second conjugation verbs add #{t "-им-", "-im-"}, and third conjugation verbs #{t "-ем-", "-em-"}. However, if the verb is third conjugation but there is no theme vowel in the infinitive (e.g., #{t "цисти", "císti"} “count”, #{abbrev 'pres'} #{t "*цед-", "ced-"}), the ending used is instead an unstressed #{t "-ом-", "-om-"}: #{t "цедоме", "cédome"} “being counted”.
  %p The passive perfective participle is the most complicated to form. There are four possible suffixes. Regularly, it is formed from the perfective infinitive stem according to the following rule:
  %ul
    %li #{t "-ен-", "-en-"} if the verb is second conjugation or third conjugation with no thematic vowel in the infinitive (e.g., цисти again). If the latter, final stem consonants are preserved intact, never dropped: #{t "поцидене", "pocídene"} “counted”. If the stem ends in a labial consonant, it will palatalize: #{t "лубити", "lubíti"} “love” → #{t "лублене", "lubléne"} “loved”.
    %li #{t "-овин-", "-ovin-"} if the verb contains the punctual suffix -на- in the infinitive. The /n/ is kept: #{t "нашнати", "naśnáti"} “begin” → #{t "нашновине", "naśnóvine"} “begun”.
    %li #{t "-т-", "-t-"} if the infinitive stem ends in /j/: #{t "оскрити", "oskríti"} “open” (stem <i>*oskrij-</i>) → #{t "оскрите", "oskríte"} “opened”. There are, however, a few second conjugation verbs that have irregularly adopted this ending, most notably #{t "затулити", "zatulíti"} “close” → #{t "затулите", "zatulíte"} “closed”.
    %li #{t "-н-", "-n-"} for first conjugation verbs or third conjugation verbs with a thematic vowel: #{t "напизати", "napizáti"} “write” → #{t "напизане", "napizáne"}.
