= section "Slavic Ablaut" do
  %p The functional load of Proto-Indo-European ablaut has largely been eliminated, with only traces visible in opaque cognates such as #{t "горѣти", "gorě́ti"} “burn” and #{t "жарити", "źáriti"} “embitter” (from PIE *gor- and *gēr- respectively) or #{t "данти", "dánti"} “blow” and #{t "диме", "díme"} “smoke” (PIE *dum- and *dūm-). Only a few verbs still show productive use of ablaut: #{t "собрати", "sobráti"} “gather”, #{t "соберун", "soberún"} “I will gather”, #{t "соборе", "sobóre"} “cathedral” (from PIE *br-, *ber-, and *bor- respectively).
  %p However, Proto-Slavic developed a new, albeit rather limited, system of ablaut that remains visible in Novegradian and most other Slavic languages. This so-called “Slavic ablaut” affects the derivation of imperfective verbs from perfective verbs.
  %p When any prefix is added to a “basic” (unprefixed) verb such as #{t "пизати", "pizáti"} “write (#{abbrev 'impf'})” or #{t "зуати", "zuáti"} “call (#{abbrev 'impf'})”, the resulting verb is perfective. One prefix for every verb loses it semantic component and becomes the perfective counterpart to the unprefixed verb: #{t "напизати", "napizáti"} “write (#{abbrev 'pf'})” (originally “write down”), #{t "позуати", "pozuáti"} “call (#{abbrev 'pf'})” (originally something along the lines of “call at”). All other prefixes have derivational functions: #{t "позпизати", "pozpizáti"} “describe (#{abbrev 'pf'})”, #{t "назуати", "nazuáti"} “name (#{abbrev 'pf'})”. These derivatives, however, now lack an imperfective counterpart. These must be back-formed from the perfective using a suffix, most commonly -ова-, and a shift to the first conjugation: #{t "позпизовати", "pozpizováti"} “sign (#{abbrev 'impf'})”. However, a small set of verbs instead form the new imperfective by ablaut: #{t "називати", "naziváti"} “call (#{abbrev 'impf'})”.
  %p This ablaut only takes place if the perfective base is second or third conjugation, and only affects the last vowel of the root. There are three types of ablaut seen:
  %ul
    %li Ø → i: #{t "собрати", "sobráti"} “gather (#{abbrev 'pf'})” → #{t "собирати", "sobiráti"} “gather (#{abbrev 'impf'})”
    %li o → a: #{t "помойкьи", "pomóikji"} “help (#{abbrev 'pf'})” → #{t "помагати", "pomagáti"} “help (#{abbrev 'impf'})”
    %li e → ě: #{t "остейкьи", "ostéikji"} “be supplied (#{abbrev 'pf'})” → #{t "остѣгати", "ostěgáti"} “be supplied (#{abbrev 'impf'})”
  %p -зуати → -зивати falls into the first category, though it has been obscured by subsequent sound changes in Novegradian. The source of this change is more obvious in Medieval Novegradian, where the perfective base was #{t "-звати", "-zvati"}.

